{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17519465","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17519465"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T14:11:35+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T14:11:35+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13023"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"13023","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/13023"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.24,0.05,0.3,0.26,0.15]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5460"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"116480"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"5460","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/5460"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13023"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"98479"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4969"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"6376"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11644"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"9262"},{"type":"contributions","id":"9717"},{"type":"contributions","id":"13405"},{"type":"contributions","id":"33426"},{"type":"contributions","id":"33930"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42839"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44386"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"116480","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/116480"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 20-year-old woman presents with a 3-day history of burning on micturition and frequency. She has associated fevers and vomiting. She denies vaginal discharge, abdominal pain or diarrhoea. She is sexually active. Apart from the oral contraceptive pill, she takes no regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EShe has an allergy to amoxicillin in which she describes dyspnoea, throat swelling, and widespread urticarial rash. She appears ill and is unable to tolerate liquids, but she is alert and orientated. Her blood pressure is 98/65 mmHg, pulse 100/min, temperature 39.4\u00a0\u00b0C and respiratory rate 20/min. There is some suprapubic and bilateral costovertebral angle tenderness.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUrinalysis reveals numerous white blood cells (WBCs) and bacteria, and it is positive for WBC casts and leukocyte esterase. Other laboratory study results are within normal limits, including a negative urine pregnancy test.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which of the following antibiotic regimens is the most appropriate?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Ceftriaxone (IV) alone","Ciprofloxacin (PO) alone","Gentamicin (IV) alone","Cefazolin and metronidazole (IV) combination","Trimethoprim-sulfamethoxazole (PO) alone"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient has a clinical picture consistent with severe pyelonephritis. The urinalysis findings of WBC support this diagnosis. Pyelonephritis\u003Cstrong\u003E \u003C/strong\u003Eis an infection of the renal parenchyma and renal pelvis, usually caused by ascending bacterial infection from the lower urinary tract. With her inability to tolerate oral fluids and a temperature of over 38.0\u003Csup\u003Eo\u003C/sup\u003EC, this patient has severe pyelonephritis and will require intravenous antibiotics. The ideal empirical treatment would be gentamicin and amoxicillin, but given her penicillin hypersensitivity, she should be given gentamicin alone. As soon as the organism is identified and/or sensitivities provided, the regimen should be de-escalated as gentamicin long-term is associated with nephrotoxicity and ototoxicity.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGentamicin\u003C/strong\u003E is effective against many gram-negative bacteria, including those commonly associated with urinary tract infections. When an alternative to beta-lactam antibiotics is required, gentamicin alone can be used as empirical monotherapy. This regimen is a suitable choice when beta-lactam antibiotics are not an option due to penicillin allergy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECeftriaxone\u003C/strong\u003E is a third-generation cephalosporin antibiotic. It provides broad-spectrum coverage against gram-negative and some gram-positive bacteria. It is often used in the treatment of severe infections. While ceftriaxone alone can be effective in treating pyelonephritis, the combination therapy is usually preferred in severe cases or when there is concern about multidrug resistance. Additionally, the stem describes previous anaphylaxis to amoxicillin, in which cephalosporins are contraindicated in individuals with an immediate penicillin hypersensitivity.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECefazolin and metronidazole combination\u003C/strong\u003E: Cefazolin is a first-generation cephalosporin that primarily provides coverage against gram-positive bacteria. Metronidazole is an antibiotic effective against anaerobic bacteria. While this combination may be used for some intra-abdominal infections, it may not provide adequate coverage for the expected pathogens in pyelonephritis. This option is less suitable for the presented case. Additionally, the stem describes previous anaphylaxis to amoxicillin, in which cephalosporins are contraindicated in individuals with an immediate penicillin hypersensitivity.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECiprofloxacin\u003C/strong\u003E is a fluoroquinolone antibiotic with excellent coverage against gram-negative bacteria, including common uropathogens. It is often used as an oral option for treating uncomplicated pyelonephritis. However, in severe cases of pyelonephritis or when the patient is unable to tolerate oral medications, intravenous antibiotics are preferred. In this case, the patient is ill and unable to tolerate liquids, making ciprofloxacin alone less suitable.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETrimethoprim-sulfamethoxazole (co-trimoxazole)\u003C/strong\u003E is a commonly used antibiotic for urinary tract infections, including pyelonephritis. It provides coverage against gram-negative and some gram-positive bacteria. It is often used as an oral option for uncomplicated cases. However, intravenous antibiotics are preferred in severe cases or when the patient cannot tolerate oral medications. In this case, intravenous antibiotics would be more appropriate when the patient is ill and unable to tolerate liquids.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["For adults with penicillin hypersensitivity, use gentamicin as a single drug (as above) for empirical therapy of severe pyelonephritis.","If susceptibility results are not available by 72 hours and empirical intravenous therapy is still required, stop the gentamicin-containing regimen and use ceftriaxone or cefotaxime as above."],"references":["Belyayeva M, Jeong JM. Acute Pyelonephritis. 2022 Sep 18. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2023 Jan\u2013. PMID: 30137822.","Ryanto S, Wong M, Czarniak P, Parsons R, Travers K, Skinner M, Sunderland B. The use of initial dosing of gentamicin in the management of pyelonephritis/urosepsis: A retrospective study. PLoS One. 2019 Jan 23;14(1):e0211094. doi: 10.1371/journal.pone.0211094. PMID: 30673763; PMCID: PMC6344021.","Emergency Care Institute. Management of pyelonephritis in adults [Internet]. Agency for Clinical Innovation (ACI); 2023 [cited 2023 Jun 17]. Available from: https://aci.health.nsw.gov.au/networks/eci/clinical/clinical-tools/renal/pyelonephritis","Therapeutic Guidelines Limited. Acute pyelonephritis in adults. In: eTG complete [Internet]. Melbourne: Therapeutic Guidelines Limited; 2025 [cited 2025 Apr 17]. Available from: https://www.tg.org.au"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"98479"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13023"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"98479","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/98479"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-29T10:54:58+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-29T10:54:58+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5460"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"116480"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"14","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/14"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udda0","name":"Infectious Diseases","synonyms":["ID"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2021-05-21T07:51:58+09:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Grad